    {
      "id": "e1945fcfafcc0eb424024db9c7239b10b4ee162e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-04-08 21:10:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nGenerally, the patch is OK for me. More suggestion about how to decide the hash bucket count (hash bits), it is better to be calculated according to the RAM size. For some fat nodes, which maybe contain more 1T RAM, current specified fixed size is relative small.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c2565834179ef620bb58bd5db7899360a3808fde",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-04-18 18:15:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, approved\n\nThis one looks good. How was it tested?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9eaf01630b87aac319bba84e667afd1ebec0dbdf",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 8,
        "name": "zhen liang",
        "email": "liang.zhen@live.com",
        "username": "liang"
      },
      "date": "2011-04-20 04:17:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOleg, there is \"CFS_HASH_DEBUG_LEVEL\" in libcfs_hash.h, default value is CFS_HASH_DEBUG_NONE, in my test, I changed it to CFS_HASH_DEBUG_2, so libcfs_hash will output information to console if there is very deep hash-table.\nIn my test, I ran mdtest with 384 mounts and millions of files, results shows that max hash depth is in very reasonable range (<= 20)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "02a4cf27c55cfd765d84c1eb7b8a09e9faae8606",
      "author": {
